{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b2db790d31558573", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tTF-MossFormer: Integrating Convolution Gated Local-Global Attentions for\n2\tEnhanced Time-Frequency Domain Monaural Speech Separation\n3\tShengkui Zhao, Zexu Pan, Haoxu Wang, Biao Tian, Bin Ma, Xiangang Li\n4\tToken Foundry, Alibaba Group, Singapore\n5\tshengkui.zhao@alibaba-inc.com\n6\t\n7\tarXiv:2607.21128v1 [cs.SD] 23 Jul 2026\n8\t\n9\tAbstract\n10\tTransformers with global attention capture long-range dependencies but can miss the fine-grained local continuity crucial for speech separation. We propose TF-MossFormer, a\n11\ttime–frequency transformer that combines local and global attention to jointly model short- and long-range contexts for\n12\tmonaural speech separation. At its core is a content-aware\n13\tsliding-window attention mechanism that dynamically adapts\n14\treceptive fields for stronger local interactions, avoiding the\n15\trigidity of static convolutions. Unlike time-domain chunkbased methods, TF-MossFormer leverages the 2D spectrogram\n16\tto model structure along both time and frequency axes. Convolutional gating between attention layers further improves feature selection and information flow. TF-MossFormer achieves\n17\tSI-SDRi of 22.6, 24.0, and 24.4 dB on WSJ0-2Mix with\n18\t5.9M, 16.9M, and 25.4M parameters, respectively, outperforming prior approaches.\n19\tIndex Terms: Transformer, local–global self-attention, convolutional gated, speech separation\n20\t\n21\t1. Introduction\n22\tSpeech separation (SS), which aims to isolate individual\n23\tsources from a mixture, is a fundamental challenge in audio\n24\tprocessing. Recent research reveals that effective modeling requires capturing both short-range continuity, such as harmonic\n25\tstructures and phoneme-level transitions, and long-range grouping, including speaker identity consistency across an utterance\n26\t[1–4]. Early end-to-end approaches like Conv-TasNet [5] highlighted the importance of local feature extraction through convolutional networks. This idea was extended by the timedomain dual-path architecture DPRNN [6], which explicitly\n27\tdecomposed the task into intra-chunk (local) and inter-chunk\n28\t(global) modeling to jointly address short- and long-range dependencies. Transformer-based models such as SepFormer [7]\n29\tand our previous MossFormer [8] and MossFormer2 [9] further\n30\tadvanced this line of work by leveraging self-attention to enhance global context modeling, leading to remarkably improved\n31\tseparation performance.\n32\tCompared with time-domain dual-path methods,\n33\ttime–frequency (TF) approaches offer a distinct advantage by leveraging the spectrogram’s two-dimensional\n34\tstructure [10–14]. For example, TF-GridNet [12] outperformed\n35\tprevious time-domain models by explicitly encoding spectrograms into separate temporal and frequency processing paths,\n36\tusing bidirectional LSTMs to preserve fine-grained continuity\n37\tand full-band self-attention to capture long-range dependencies\n38\tacross the entire spectrogram. Building on this framework, SPMamba [13] replaced recurrent blocks with state-space models,\n39\tshowing that alternative sequential operators can deliver better\n40\t\n41\t(a) Global attention\n42\t\n43\t(b) Local attention\n44\t\n45\tFig. 1: Illustration of the global and local attention patterns in\n46\tTF-MossFormer. (a) Global attention: captures long-range dependencies across the entire spectrogram, (b) Local attention:\n47\tfocuses on fine-grained continuity within sliding windows.\n48\t\n49\tlocal modeling at lower cost. Conformer-based methods [10]\n50\ttake a complementary approach by embedding convolutional\n51\tmodules inside attention blocks, explicitly fusing locality and\n52\tcontext to improve the modeling of short-range transients.\n53\tTF-LocoFormer [14] further complements global attention\n54\twith gated convolutional layers to more tightly integrate local\n55\tspectral detail and global aggregation, yielding notable gains in\n56\tseparation performance. These prior works motivate our focus\n57\ton adaptive local mechanisms that enhance spectral continuity\n58\twhile preserving global modeling capabilities based on the TF\n59\tdomain geometry.\n60\tThe shift toward hybrid local–global modeling is a broader\n61\ttrend beyond speech processing. In natural language processing\n62\t(NLP), models like Longformer [15] and BigBird [16] combine\n63\tlocal attention with global tokens to efficiently handle long sequences. Similarly, in computer vision, PLG-ViT [17] and BiFormer [18] use parallel attention to capture both fine details\n64\tand scene-level context. These approaches reflect a broader\n65\tneed to model both local patterns and long-range dependencies in sequential data. Inspired by these cross-domain innovations, we introduce TF-MossFormer, a time–frequency framework for monaural speech separation. Our model integrates\n66\thybrid local–global attention in a unified architecture to preserve short-range spectral continuity while capturing long-range\n67\tdependencies in speech spectrograms. As shown in Fig. 1,\n68\tsliding-window local attention focuses on fine-grained spectral\n69\tfeatures, retaining subtle temporal and harmonic details, while\n70\tglobal attention spans wider regions to capture speaker-specific\n71\tcharacteristics. We further enhance both pathways with convolutional gating to improve representation. We evaluate the\n72\tperformance of TF-MossFormer through extensive experiments\n73\ton the widely-used WSJ0-2Mix benchmark.\n74\t\n75\t\fOutput\n76\tPermute\n77\t\n78\tV1\n79\t\n80\tV2\n81\t\n82\tiSTFT\n83\tImag.\n84\t\n85\tReal\n86\t\n87\tx TF-TMossFormer blocks\n88\t\n89\tDeconv2D\n90\t\n91\tConv-SwiGLU\n92\t\n93\tTemporal\n94\tModeling\n95\tLocal & Global\n96\tMHSA\n97\tFrequency\n98\tModeling\n99\tRMSGroupNorm\n100\t\n101\tGlobal\n102\tMHSA\n103\t\n104\tGate\n105\t\n106\tLocal\n107\tMHSA\n108\t\n109\tGate\n110\t\n111\tLocal\n112\tMHSA\n113\t\n114\tGate\n115\t\n116\tGlobal\n117\tMHSA\n118\t\n119\tGate\n120\t\n121\tV3\n122\t\n123\tConv2D + gLN\n124\tReal\n125\t\n126\tSwish\n127\t\n128\tImag.\n129\t\n130\tConv-SwiGLU\n131\t\n132\tSTFT\n133\t\n134\tGate\n135\t\n136\tGlobal\n137\tMHSA\n138\t\n139\tLocal\n140\tMHSA\n141\t\n142\tGate\n143\tConv1D\n144\t\n145\tPermute\n146\tInput\n147\t\n148\t(a)\n149\t\n150\t(b)\n151\t\n152\t(c)\n153\t\n154\tFig. 2: Overview of TF-MossFormer. (a) Model flowchart with STFT/ISTFT, Conv2D/Deconv2D, gLN, and B stacked TF-MossFormer\n155\tblocks for interleaved time–frequency modeling. (b) Configuration of the frequency modeling block (the temporal block adopts the\n156\tsame structure). (c) Three variants (V1–V3) of the gated local–global MHSA module. ⊕: element-wise addition, ⊗: element-wise\n157\tmultiplication.\n158\t\n159\t2. The TF-MossFormer Model\n160\tPC\n161\t\n162\tGiven a speech mixture x = i=1 si , our goal is to estimate\n163\tthe C individual sources si ∈ R1×L , i = 1, 2, . . . , C using a\n164\tdeep learning model. The proposed TF-MossFormer adopts the\n165\tdual-path time–frequency separation paradigm [12], preserving the encoder–separator–decoder architecture. Unlike timedomain approaches that operate on two-dimensional chunks and\n166\tpredict time-domain masks, TF-MossFormer operates in the\n167\tshort-time Fourier transform (STFT) domain and directly predicts both the real and imaginary components of the complex\n168\tspectra.\n169\t\n170\t2.2. The Encoder and Decoder\n171\tOur TF-MossFormer adopts the encoder and decoder design\n172\tfrom TF-GridNet. The encoder consists of a 3 × 3 2D convolution (Conv2D) layer with D output channels, followed\n173\tby global layer normalization (gLN). This step projects each\n174\ttime–frequency (T–F) unit into a D-dimensional latent embedding, resulting in a tensor of shape D × T × F . The decoder\n175\tmirrors the encoder by applying a 3 × 3 2D transposed convolution (Deconv2D) with 2C output channels, representing the predicted real and imaginary components for all C target sources.\n176\t2.3. The TF-MossFormer Separator\n177\t\n178\t2.1. Overview of TF-MossFormer Architecture\n179\tFig. 2 illustrates our TF-MossFormer architecture. The\n180\tinput mixture waveform x is first transformed into the\n181\ttime–frequency domain using STFT, producing real and imaginary components XReal ∈ RT ×F and XImag. ∈ RT ×F , where\n182\tT and F are the number of frames and frequency bins. The\n183\treal and imaginary parts are concatenated as X ∈ R2×T ×F\n184\tand passed through a 2D convolutional (Conv2D) encoder followed by global Layer Normalization (gLN) to project the features into a feature representative space. The core separator\n185\tconsists of B stacked TF-MossFormer blocks, each comprising two sub-modules: the frequency module and the temporal\n186\tmodule. Both modules share the same architecture but perform on alternative sequence dimensions. The frequency module models spectral dependencies across frequency bins along\n187\tthe frequency path, while the temporal module models temporal dependencies across time frames along the time path. By\n188\talternately modeling frequency and time dependencies, the network progressively refines the representation while efficiently\n189\tcovering the entire time–frequency context. The decoder uses a\n190\ttransposed convolution (Deconv2D) layer to reconstruct the estimated real and imaginary spectra, which are then transformed\n191\tback to the time domain using the inverse STFT (iSTFT) to obtain the separated waveform signals.\n192\t\n193\tThe encoded representation is passed to the TF-MossFormer\n194\tseparator, which consists of B stacked TF-MossFormer blocks.\n195\tWithin each block, the spectro-temporal modeling is performed\n196\tto progressively refine the local–global dependencies for the\n197\tlatent TF embeddings. As depicted in Fig. 2(a), each TFMossFormer block contains two sequential modeling modules:\n198\ta frequency modeling module and a temporal modeling module, both sharing an identical architecture. The module architecture is shown in Fig. 1(b), where the input tensor is first\n199\tpermuted to align the modeling dimension (frequency or time)\n200\twith the sequence axis. The permuted input is passed through a\n201\tconvolutional SwiGLU feed-forward network (Conv-SwiGLU)\n202\t[14], followed by a residual connection to preserve the original representation. Next, Root Mean Square Group Normalization (RMSGroupNorm) [14] is applied to stabilize training and\n203\timprove convergence. The normalized features are then processed by the core Local & Global Multi-Head Self-Attention\n204\t(MHSA) module, which integrates content-aware local attention (via sliding windows) and global attention to jointly model\n205\tfine-grained dependencies and long-range context. The output\n206\tis again passed through a Conv-SwiGLU module and added\n207\tback via residual connection before being permuted back to its\n208\toriginal shape. This design ensures balanced local and global\n209\trepresentation learning while maintaining efficiency through\n210\t\n211\t\fTable 1: Hyperparameter notations and model configurations\n212\tfor TF-MambaFormer (S), (M), and (L).\n213\t\n214\tLinear\n215\tConcat\n216\t\n217\tSymbol Description\n218\th\n219\t\n220\tScaled Dot-Product Attention\n221\t\n222\tLinear\n223\t\n224\tLinear\n225\t\n226\tLinear\n227\t\n228\tFig. 3: An overview of the local attention module, which performs multi-head self-attention using sliding windows. Each\n229\tattention head operates on a fixed-size window of the input sequence.\n230\tresidual pathways and normalization.\n231\t2.3.1. Convolution Gated Local and Global Attention\n232\tWe apply both local and global attention with convolution gating in the TF-MossFormer separator to capture complementary\n233\tshort- and long-range dependencies in speech spectrograms.\n234\tOur global attention is a standard Multi-Head Self-Attention\n235\t(MHSA) mechanism [19], every frame in a sequence attends\n236\tto every other frame as depicted in Fig. 1(a). For the temporal\n237\tsequence X ∈ RT ×D T, the query (Qi ), key (Ki ), and value\n238\t(Vi ) matrices are the i-th head projections of size T ×dh , where\n239\tdh = D/h is the hidden dimension of each head. Our global\n240\tMHSA computes the attention of each head as:\n241\t\u0012\n242\t\u0013\n243\tQi K ⊤\n244\theadglobal,i = softmax √ i\n245\tVi .\n246\t(1)\n247\tdh\n248\tAll heads are concatenated to form the full attention matrix:\n249\t\u0001\n250\tMHSAglobal (X) = Concat headglobal,1 , . . . , headglobal,h WO ,\n251\t(2)\n252\twhere WO is the output projection matrix. This operation has\n253\tcomplexity O(T 2 D) due to the dense QK ⊤ computation.\n254\tComplementing the global attention, we present local attention to focus on short-range time–frequency patterns to preserve fine-grained continuity. As depicted in Fig. 1(b), it captures context at varying distances from each frame. Our local attention adopts the sliding-window multi-head attention as\n255\tdepicted in Fig. 3. The local attention restricts each frame\n256\tt to attend only to frames within a local window N (t) =\n257\t{t − w−1\n258\t, . . . , t, . . . , t + w−1\n259\t}, where w is the window size.\n260\t2\n261\t2\n262\tThe attention for head i becomes:\n263\t\u0012\n264\t\u0013\n265\tQi (t)Ki (N (t))⊤\n266\t√\n267\theadlocal,i (t) = softmax\n268\tVi (N (t)),\n269\tdh\n270\t(3)\n271\twhere Qi (t) ∈ R1×dh is the query for frame t, Ki (N (t)) ∈\n272\tRw×dh are the keys within the window, and Vi (N (t)) are the\n273\tcorresponding values. This reduces complexity to O(T wD),\n274\twhich scales linearly with T for a fixed w.\n275\tWe further augment local and global attention with convolutional gates as shown in Fig. 2(c). The gate consists of a\n276\tConv1D layer followed by Swish activation. Since attention ordering affects performance, we implemented three block variants (V1-V3) and ran an ablation study to identify the most effective arrangement for our model.\n277\t\n278\tS\n279\t\n280\tM\n281\t\n282\tL\n283\t\n284\tD\n285\tB\n286\tH\n287\tO\n288\tK\n289\tS\n290\th\n291\twF\n292\twT\n293\t\n294\tEmbedding dimension of each TF bin\n295\t96 128 128\n296\tNumber of TF-MossFormer blocks\n297\t4 6\n298\t9\n299\tHidden dimension in Conv-SwiGLU\n300\t256 384 384\n301\tOutput dimension in Conv-Gate\n302\t96 128 128\n303\tKernel size in Conv1D and Deconv1D\n304\t4 4\n305\t4\n306\tStride in Conv1D and Deconv1D\n307\t1 1\n308\t1\n309\tNumber of heads in self-attention\n310\t4 4 4\n311\tSliding-window length for frequency path 7 7 7\n312\tSliding-window length for temporal path 31 31 31\n313\t\n314\t−\n315\t\n316\tNumber of parameters [M]\n317\t\n318\t6.0 16.9 25.4\n319\t\n320\t2.3.2. The Convolution Modules\n321\tLocal attention captures nearby context but needs many layers\n322\tfor broader integration. To improve global feature mixing efficiently, we add Conv-SwiGLU blocks (Fig. 2(b)), combining attention’s adaptive weighting with convolutional feature\n323\textraction. Each block applies RMSGroupNorm, two parallel\n324\t1D convolutions, a Swish-gated element-wise modulation, and\n325\ta final 1D deconvolution to restore embedding size. Following [14], we place Conv-SwiGLU before and after the local and\n326\tglobal attention layers.\n327\t\n328\t3. Experiments\n329\t3.1. Dataset & Experimental Setup\n330\tWe validated our proposed TF-MossFormer on the widely-used\n331\tWSJ0-2mix dataset, which benchmarks monaural speech separation. The dataset is comprised of three distinct sets: a training\n332\tset of 20,000 ( 30 hours), a validation set of 5,000 ( 10 hours),\n333\tand a test set of 3,000 ( 5 hours) two-speaker mixtures. The\n334\tclean utterances are sourced from the WSJ0 corpus. In each\n335\tmixture, the two utterances are randomly selected from WSJ0\n336\tand fully overlapped, with their relative energy levels randomly\n337\tchosen from the signal-to-noise ratios (SNR) between -5 dB and\n338\t5 dB. The test set is generated in the same way. Notably, speakers in the test set are distinct from those in the training and validation sets, ensuring a non-blind evaluation. All audio clips are\n339\tsampled at 8 kHz.\n340\tAll experiments were conducted using the ESPnet pipeline\n341\twith SI-SDR loss [20]. Table 1 summarizes the key hyperparameters and default configurations for our three model sizes.\n342\tFor data preparation, we used a 16 ms STFT window with an\n343\t8 ms hop size and segmented all input audio into 4 s clips. Each\n344\tmixture was normalized by its standard deviation, and the batch\n345\tsize was set to 4. For optimization, we employed the AdamW\n346\toptimizer [21] with a weight decay of 1 × 10−2 . The learning\n347\trate was linearly warmed up to 1 × 10−3 during the first 4,000\n348\tsteps, followed by a scheduler that halved the learning rate if the\n349\tvalidation loss failed to improve for three consecutive epochs.\n350\tTraining was conducted for up to 150 epochs, with early stopping applied after 10 stagnant epochs. To ensure stability, the\n351\tL2 norm of the gradient was clipped to 5.\n352\t3.2. Ablation Study\n353\tAs shown in Table 2, we evaluated several sliding-window configurations for TF-MossFormer (S) on WSJ0-2Mix, keeping the\n354\twindow length identical across all attention heads for ease of\n355\ttuning. The setting of wT = 31 and wF = 7 achieves the best\n356\t\n357\t\fTable 2: Ablation study of TF-MossFormer performance with\n358\tdifferent sliding-window lengths.\n359\tModel (S)\n360\t\n361\tTable 4: Performance comparison of TF-MossFormer (S) with\n362\tstate-of-the-art models of similar scale on the WSJ0-2Mix\n363\tdataset.\n364\t\n365\tSliding-Window(wT , wF ) SI-SDRi SDRi MACS [G/s]\n366\t\n367\tTF-MossFormer\n368\tTF-MossFormer\n369\tTF-MossFormer\n370\tTF-MossFormer\n371\tTF-MossFormer\n372\tTF-MossFormer\n373\t\n374\t(31, 7)\n375\t(15, 7)\n376\t(65, 7)\n377\t(31, 3)\n378\t(31, 15)\n379\tFull Length\n380\t\n381\t22.61\n382\t22.51\n383\t22.56\n384\t22.53\n385\t22.47\n386\t22.38\n387\t\n388\t22.77\n389\t22.68\n390\t22.73\n391\t22.69\n392\t22.66\n393\t22.58\n394\t\n395\t99.5\n396\t99.4\n397\t99.7\n398\t99.5\n399\t99.5\n400\t100.3\n401\t\n402\tTable 3: Ablation study of TF-MossFormer performance with\n403\tdifferent configurations of local-global attention.\n404\tModel (S)\n405\tTF-MossFormer(V1)\n406\tTF-MossFormer(V2)\n407\tTF-MossFormer(V3)\n408\tTF-MossFormer(V4)\n409\t\n410\tSliding-Window(T-F) SI-SDRi SDRi MACS [G/s]\n411\t(31, 7)\n412\t(31, 7)\n413\t(31, 7)\n414\t(31, 7)\n415\t\n416\t22.61\n417\t22.45\n418\t22.49\n419\t22.51\n420\t\n421\t22.77\n422\t22.60\n423\t22.63\n424\t22.62\n425\t\n426\t99.5\n427\t99.5\n428\t99.5\n429\t99.3\n430\t\n431\tresult, with 22.61 dB SI-SDRi (22.77 dB SDRi) while maintaining manageable computation at 99.5 G MACS/s, slightly\n432\toutperforming both the narrower 15-frame and the wider 65frame time windows. A frequency span of 7 bands is also\n433\tpreferable to smaller (3 bands) or larger (15 bands) choices. Using full-length windows yields the weakest performance (22.38\n434\tdB). These results indicate that TF-MossFormer favors moderate time–frequency window sizes that balance local detail and\n435\tefficiency. Table 3 evaluates the local–global attention layouts and convolution gating for TF-MossFormer (S) on WSJ02Mix. All models used the (31,7) sliding window. The cascade ordering—local attention followed by global attention\n436\t(V1)—achieves the best results (22.61 dB SI-SDRi, 22.77 dB\n437\tSDRi). Reversing the order (V2) reduces SI-SDRi to 22.45 dB,\n438\twhile the parallel local–global design (V3) performs slightly\n439\tbetter than V2 (22.49 dB). Removing convolutional gating from\n440\tV1 (V4) also degrades performance to 22.51 dB. These findings\n441\tsuggest that applying local attention before global aggregation\n442\thelps preserve fine-grained spectral continuity, and that convolutional gating yields measurable gains in feature selection.\n443\t3.3. Experimental Results\n444\tOur experimental results on WSJ0-2Mix, presented in Tables\n445\t4 and 5, comprehensively evaluate TF-MossFormer (configuration V1) across three model scales. The small-scale variant TFMossFormer(S), with just 6.0M parameters and 99.5 G MACS/s\n446\tcomputational cost, achieves 22.61 dB SI-SDRi (22.77 dB\n447\tSDRi), demonstrating superior separation quality compared to\n448\tother compact models. It notably outperforms both the standard\n449\tTF-Locoformer(S) and our reproduced TF-Locoformer(S*)\n450\twith increased dimensionality (D =112), which achieves 22.2\n451\tdB SI-SDRi at higher computational cost. The comparison with\n452\tSPMamba is particularly revealing - TF-MossFormer(S) delivers better performance (by 0.1 dB SI-SDRi) while requiring\n453\tless than half the computations, highlighting our architecture’s\n454\tefficiency advantages. At medium scale, TF-MossFormer(M)\n455\t(16.9M parameters, 283.4 G MACS/s) reaches 24.0 dB SI-SDRi\n456\t(24.20 dB SDRi), significantly surpassing both TF-GridNet and\n457\tTF-Locoformer(M) in performance while maintaining substantially lower computational requirements than TF-GridNet. This\n458\tdemonstrates excellent scaling properties of our architecture.\n459\tThe large-scale TF-MossFormer(L) (25.4M parameters, 425.0\n460\tG MACS/s) establishes new state-of-the-art results with 24.4 dB\n461\t\n462\tModel (S)\n463\t\n464\tParam.[M] SI-SDRi SDRi MACS [G/s]\n465\t\n466\tConv-TasNet [5]\n467\t\n468\t5.6\n469\t\n470\t15.3\n471\t\n472\t15.6\n473\t\n474\t10.23\n475\t\n476\tA-FRCNN [22]\n477\tDualPathRNN [6]\n478\tVSUNOS [23]\n479\tDPTNet [4]\n480\tS4M [24]\n481\tSepMamba+DM [25]\n482\tDPMamba [26]\n483\tTF-Locoformer(S) [14]\n484\tTF-Locoformer(S*) [14]\n485\tSPMamba [13]\n486\t\n487\t6.1\n488\t2.6\n489\t7.5\n490\t2.6\n491\t3.6\n492\t7.2\n493\t8.1\n494\t5.0\n495\t6.0\n496\t6.1\n497\t\n498\t18.3\n499\t18.8\n500\t20.1\n501\t20.2\n502\t20.5\n503\t21.2\n504\t21.4\n505\t22.0\n506\t22.2\n507\t22.5\n508\t\n509\t18.6\n510\t19.0\n511\t20.4\n512\t20.6\n513\t20.7\n514\t21.4\n515\t21.6\n516\t22.1\n517\t22.3\n518\t22.7\n519\t\n520\t125.3\n521\t85.3\n522\t102.5\n523\t38.7\n524\t85.9\n525\t100.3\n526\t238.6\n527\t\n528\tTF-MossFormer(S)\n529\t\n530\t6.0\n531\t\n532\t22.6\n533\t\n534\t22.8\n535\t\n536\t99.5\n537\t\n538\tTable 5: Performance comparison of TF-MossFormer (M) and\n539\t(L) with state-of-the-art models of similar scale on the WSJ02Mix dataset.\n540\tModel (M&L)\n541\t\n542\tParam.[M] SI-SDRi SDRi MACS [G/s]\n543\t\n544\tTF-GridNet [12]\n545\tTF-Locoformer (M) [14]\n546\tTF-MossFormer(M)\n547\t\n548\t14.4\n549\t15.0\n550\t16.9\n551\t\n552\t23.5\n553\t23.6\n554\t24.0\n555\t\n556\t23.6\n557\t23.8\n558\t24.2\n559\t\n560\t445.5\n561\t251.1\n562\t283.4\n563\t\n564\tWavesplit [27]\n565\tSepFormer+DM [7]\n566\tSepMamba+DM [25]\n567\tMossFormer(L)+DM [8]\n568\tDPMamba [26]\n569\tQPDN [28]\n570\tSepTDA2 [29]\n571\tMossFormer2(L)+DM [9]\n572\tTF-Locoformer(L) [14]\n573\t\n574\t29.0\n575\t25.7\n576\t22.0\n577\t42.1\n578\t59.8\n579\t200\n580\t21.2\n581\t55.7\n582\t22.6\n583\t\n584\t22.2\n585\t22.3\n586\t22.7\n587\t22.8\n588\t23.4\n589\t23.6\n590\t24.0\n591\t24.1\n592\t24.2\n593\t\n594\t22.3\n595\t22.4\n596\t22.9\n597\t23.6\n598\t23.9\n599\t24.3\n600\t\n601\t257.9\n602\t256.7\n603\t336.9\n604\t377.1\n605\t\n606\tTF-MossFormer(L)\n607\t\n608\t25.4\n609\t\n610\t24.4\n611\t\n612\t24.5\n613\t\n614\t425.0\n615\t\n616\tSI-SDRi (24.5 dB SDRi), outperforming all frequency-domain\n617\tcompetitors including TF-Locoformer(L) and SepTDA2 , as\n618\twell as challenging time-domain baselines like MossFormer\n619\tand MossFormer2 with dynamic mixing. These consistent gains\n620\tacross all model sizes, from compact to large configurations, robustly validate the effectiveness of our local-global attention design in achieving superior separation quality while maintaining\n621\tcomputational efficiency. The results particularly highlight our\n622\tarchitecture’s advantage in modeling both fine-grained spectrotemporal details and long-range dependencies simultaneously.\n623\t\n624\t4. Conclusion\n625\tWe presented TF-MossFormer, a hybrid time–frequency transformer that combines adaptive local attention with global attention for monaural speech separation. Our main contributions are: (1) content-aware sliding-window attention for\n626\tadaptive spectro-temporal modeling; (2) an optimized local–global attention configuration; and (3) convolutional gating to improve feature selection and information flow. Extensive experiments on WSJ0-2Mix show that TF-MossFormer\n627\tdelivers state-of-the-art separation performance across multiple model scales while maintaining favorable parameter and\n628\tcomputation efficiency compared to existing time-domain and\n629\tfrequency-domain baselines.\n630\t\n631\t\f5. References\n632\t[1] H. Erdogan, J. R. Hershey, S. Watanabe, and J. L. Roux, “Phase\n633\tsensitive and recognition-boosted speech separation using deep\n634\trecurrent neural networks,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2015, p. 708–712.\n635\t[2] Y. Luo and N. Mesgarani, “TasNet: time-domain audio separation\n636\tnetwork for real-time, single-channel speech separation,” in Proc.\n637\tof ICASSP, 2018.\n638\t\n639\t[21] I. Loshchilov and F. Hutter, “Decoupled weight decay regularization,” in Proc. ICLR, 2018.\n640\t[22] X. Hu, K. Li, W. Zhang, Y. Luo, J.-M. Lemercier, and T. Gerkmann, “Speech separation using an asynchronous fully recurrent\n641\tconvolutional neural network,” in Proc. of NeurIPS, 2021.\n642\t[23] E. Nachmani, Y. Adi, and L. Wolf, “Voice separation with an unknown number of multiple speakers,” in Proc. of ICML, 2020.\n643\t\n644\t[3] ——, “Real-time single-channel dereverberation and separation\n645\twith time-domain audio separation network,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2018.\n646\t\n647\t[24] C. Chen, C.-H. H. Yang, K. Li, Y. Hu, P.-J. Ku, and E. S. Chng, “A\n648\tneural state-space model approach to efficient speech separation,”\n649\tin Proc. of Interspeech, 2023.\n650\t\n651\t[4] J. Chen, Q. Mao, and D. Liu, “Dual-Path Transformer Network:\n652\tDirect context-aware modeling for end-to-end monaural speech\n653\tseparation,” in Proc. of Interspeech, 2020.\n654\t\n655\t[25] T. H. Avenstrup, B. Elek, I. L. Mádi, A. B. Schin, M. Mørup,\n656\tB. S. Jensen, and K. F. Olsen, “SepMamba: State-space models\n657\tfor speaker separation using mamba,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2024.\n658\t\n659\t[5] Y. Luo and N. Mesgarani, “Conv-TasNet: Surpassing ideal\n660\ttime–frequency magnitude masking for speech separation,”\n661\tIEEE/ACM transactions on audio, speech, and language processing, vol. 27, no. 8, p. 1256–1266, 2019.\n662\t\n663\t[26] X. Jiang, C. Han, and N. Mesgarani, “Dual-path Mamba: Short\n664\tand long-term bidirectional selective structured state space models for speech separation,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2025.\n665\t\n666\t[6] Y. Luo, Z. Chen, and T. Yoshioka, “Dual-Path RNN: Efficient long\n667\tsequence modeling for time-domain single-channel speech separation,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2020.\n668\t[7] C. Subakan, M. Ravanelli, S. Cornell, M. Bronzi, and J. Zhong,\n669\t“Attention is all you need in speech separation,” in Proc. of\n670\tICASSP, 2021.\n671\t[8] S. Zhao and B. Ma, “MossFormer: Pushing the performance\n672\tlimit of monaural speech separation using gated single-head transformer with convolution-augmented joint self-attentions,” in Proc.\n673\tof ICASSP, 2023.\n674\t[9] S. Zhao, Y. Ma, C. Ni, C. Zhang, H. Wang, T. H. Nguyen,\n675\tK. Zhou, J. Yip, D. Ng, and B. Ma, “MossFormer2: Combining transformer and rnn-free recurrent network for enhanced timedomain monaural speech separation,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2024.\n676\t[10] S. Chen, Y. Wu, Z. Chen, J. Wu, J. Li, T. Yoshioka, C. Wang,\n677\tS. Liu, and M. Zhou, “Continuous speech separation with conformer,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2021, pp. 5749–5753.\n678\t[11] L. Yang, W. Liu, and W. Wang, “TFPSNet: Time-frequency domain path scanning network for speech separation,” in Proc. of\n679\tICASSP, 2022.\n680\t[12] Z.-Q. Wang, S. Cornell, S. Choi, Y. Lee, B.-Y. Kim, and S. Watanabe, “TF-GridNet: Making time-frequency domain models great\n681\tagain for monaural speaker separation,” arXiv:2209.03952, 2023.\n682\t[13] K. Li, G. Chen, R. Yang, and X. Hu, “SPMamba: State-space\n683\tmodel is all you need in speech separation,” arXiv:2404.02063,\n684\t2024.\n685\t[14] K. Saijo, G. Wichern, F. G. Germain, Z. Pan, and J. L. Roux, “TFLocoformer: Transformer with local modeling by convolution for\n686\tspeech separation and enhancement,” in 2024 18th International\n687\tWorkshop on Acoustic Signal Enhancement (IWAENC), 2024.\n688\t[15] I. Beltagy, M. E. Peters, and A. Cohan, “Longformer: The longdocument transformer,” arXiv:2004.05150, 2020.\n689\t[16] M. Zaheer, G. Guruganesh, K. A. Dubey, J. Ainslie, C. Alberti,\n690\tS. Ontanon, P. Pham, A. Ravula, Q. Wang, L. Yang et al., “Big\n691\tbird: Transformers for longer sequences,” Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, vol. 33, 2020.\n692\t[17] N. Ebert, L. Reichardt, D. Stricker, and O. Wasenmüller, “Lightweight vision transformer with parallel local and global selfattention,” arXiv:2307.09120, 2023.\n693\t[18] L. Zhu, X. Wang, Z. Ke, W. Zhang, and R. Lau, “Biformer: Vision\n694\ttransformer with bi-level routing attention,” Proceedings of the\n695\tIEEE/CVF Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR), 2023.\n696\t[19] A. Vaswani, N. Shazeer, N. Parmar, J. Uszkoreit, L. Jones, A. N.\n697\tGomez, L. Kaiser, and I. Polosukhin, “Attention is all you need,”\n698\tin Proc. NIPS, 2017.\n699\t[20] C. Li, J. Shi, W. Zhang, A. S. Subramanian, X. Chang et al.,\n700\t“ESPnet-SE: End-to-end speech enhancement and separation\n701\ttoolkit designed for asr integration,” in Proc. SLT, 2021.\n702\t\n703\t[27] N. Zeghidour and D. Grangier, “Wavesplit: End-to-end speech\n704\tseparation by speaker clustering,” IEEE/ACM Trans. Audio.\n705\tSpeech, Lang. Process., vol. 29, 2021.\n706\t[28] J. Rixen and M. Renz, “QDPN - Quasi-dual-path Network for\n707\tsingle-channel Speech Separation,” in Proc. Interspeech 2022,\n708\t2022, pp. 5353–5357.\n709\t[29] Y. Lee, S. Choi, B.-Y. Kim, Z.-Q. Wang, and S. Watanabe,\n710\t“Boosting unknown-number speaker separation with transformer\n711\tdecoder-based attractor,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2024.\n712\t\n713\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "9f738fdd-4afe-4d24-b110-e35ffef7b511", "uuid": "e644bb7c-f101-4b69-a29c-f3d87afc9c77", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T05:51:53.998Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/tfmoss.txt", "content": "TF-MossFormer: Integrating Convolution Gated Local-Global Attentions for\nEnhanced Time-Frequency Domain Monaural Speech Separation\nShengkui Zhao, Zexu Pan, Haoxu Wang, Biao Tian, Bin Ma, Xiangang Li\nToken Foundry, Alibaba Group, Singapore\nshengkui.zhao@alibaba-inc.com\n\narXiv:2607.21128v1 [cs.SD] 23 Jul 2026\n\nAbstract\nTransformers with global attention capture long-range dependencies but can miss the fine-grained local continuity crucial for speech separation. We propose TF-MossFormer, a\ntime–frequency transformer that combines local and global attention to jointly model short- and long-range contexts for\nmonaural speech separation. At its core is a content-aware\nsliding-window attention mechanism that dynamically adapts\nreceptive fields for stronger local interactions, avoiding the\nrigidity of static convolutions. Unlike time-domain chunkbased methods, TF-MossFormer leverages the 2D spectrogram\nto model structure along both time and frequency axes. Convolutional gating between attention layers further improves feature selection and information flow. TF-MossFormer achieves\nSI-SDRi of 22.6, 24.0, and 24.4 dB on WSJ0-2Mix with\n5.9M, 16.9M, and 25.4M parameters, respectively, outperforming prior approaches.\nIndex Terms: Transformer, local–global self-attention, convolutional gated, speech separation\n\n1. Introduction\nSpeech separation (SS), which aims to isolate individual\nsources from a mixture, is a fundamental challenge in audio\nprocessing. Recent research reveals that effective modeling requires capturing both short-range continuity, such as harmonic\nstructures and phoneme-level transitions, and long-range grouping, including speaker identity consistency across an utterance\n[1–4]. Early end-to-end approaches like Conv-TasNet [5] highlighted the importance of local feature extraction through convolutional networks. This idea was extended by the timedomain dual-path architecture DPRNN [6], which explicitly\ndecomposed the task into intra-chunk (local) and inter-chunk\n(global) modeling to jointly address short- and long-range dependencies. Transformer-based models such as SepFormer [7]\nand our previous MossFormer [8] and MossFormer2 [9] further\nadvanced this line of work by leveraging self-attention to enhance global context modeling, leading to remarkably improved\nseparation performance.\nCompared with time-domain dual-path methods,\ntime–frequency (TF) approaches offer a distinct advantage by leveraging the spectrogram’s two-dimensional\nstructure [10–14]. For example, TF-GridNet [12] outperformed\nprevious time-domain models by explicitly encoding spectrograms into separate temporal and frequency processing paths,\nusing bidirectional LSTMs to preserve fine-grained continuity\nand full-band self-attention to capture long-range dependencies\nacross the entire spectrogram. Building on this framework, SPMamba [13] replaced recurrent blocks with state-space models,\nshowing that alternative sequential operators can deliver better\n\n(a) Global attention\n\n(b) Local attention\n\nFig. 1: Illustration of the global and local attention patterns in\nTF-MossFormer. (a) Global attention: captures long-range dependencies across the entire spectrogram, (b) Local attention:\nfocuses on fine-grained continuity within sliding windows.\n\nlocal modeling at lower cost. Conformer-based methods [10]\ntake a complementary approach by embedding convolutional\nmodules inside attention blocks, explicitly fusing locality and\ncontext to improve the modeling of short-range transients.\nTF-LocoFormer [14] further complements global attention\nwith gated convolutional layers to more tightly integrate local\nspectral detail and global aggregation, yielding notable gains in\nseparation performance. These prior works motivate our focus\non adaptive local mechanisms that enhance spectral continuity\nwhile preserving global modeling capabilities based on the TF\ndomain geometry.\nThe shift toward hybrid local–global modeling is a broader\ntrend beyond speech processing. In natural language processing\n(NLP), models like Longformer [15] and BigBird [16] combine\nlocal attention with global tokens to efficiently handle long sequences. Similarly, in computer vision, PLG-ViT [17] and BiFormer [18] use parallel attention to capture both fine details\nand scene-level context. These approaches reflect a broader\nneed to model both local patterns and long-range dependencies in sequential data. Inspired by these cross-domain innovations, we introduce TF-MossFormer, a time–frequency framework for monaural speech separation. Our model integrates\nhybrid local–global attention in a unified architecture to preserve short-range spectral continuity while capturing long-range\ndependencies in speech spectrograms. As shown in Fig. 1,\nsliding-window local attention focuses on fine-grained spectral\nfeatures, retaining subtle temporal and harmonic details, while\nglobal attention spans wider regions to capture speaker-specific\ncharacteristics. We further enhance both pathways with convolutional gating to improve representation. We evaluate the\nperformance of TF-MossFormer through extensive experiments\non the widely-used WSJ0-2Mix benchmark.\n\n\fOutput\nPermute\n\nV1\n\nV2\n\niSTFT\nImag.\n\nReal\n\nx TF-TMossFormer blocks\n\nDeconv2D\n\nConv-SwiGLU\n\nTemporal\nModeling\nLocal & Global\nMHSA\nFrequency\nModeling\nRMSGroupNorm\n\nGlobal\nMHSA\n\nGate\n\nLocal\nMHSA\n\nGate\n\nLocal\nMHSA\n\nGate\n\nGlobal\nMHSA\n\nGate\n\nV3\n\nConv2D + gLN\nReal\n\nSwish\n\nImag.\n\nConv-SwiGLU\n\nSTFT\n\nGate\n\nGlobal\nMHSA\n\nLocal\nMHSA\n\nGate\nConv1D\n\nPermute\nInput\n\n(a)\n\n(b)\n\n(c)\n\nFig. 2: Overview of TF-MossFormer. (a) Model flowchart with STFT/ISTFT, Conv2D/Deconv2D, gLN, and B stacked TF-MossFormer\nblocks for interleaved time–frequency modeling. (b) Configuration of the frequency modeling block (the temporal block adopts the\nsame structure). (c) Three variants (V1–V3) of the gated local–global MHSA module. ⊕: element-wise addition, ⊗: element-wise\nmultiplication.\n\n2. The TF-MossFormer Model\nPC\n\nGiven a speech mixture x = i=1 si , our goal is to estimate\nthe C individual sources si ∈ R1×L , i = 1, 2, . . . , C using a\ndeep learning model. The proposed TF-MossFormer adopts the\ndual-path time–frequency separation paradigm [12], preserving the encoder–separator–decoder architecture. Unlike timedomain approaches that operate on two-dimensional chunks and\npredict time-domain masks, TF-MossFormer operates in the\nshort-time Fourier transform (STFT) domain and directly predicts both the real and imaginary components of the complex\nspectra.\n\n2.2. The Encoder and Decoder\nOur TF-MossFormer adopts the encoder and decoder design\nfrom TF-GridNet. The encoder consists of a 3 × 3 2D convolution (Conv2D) layer with D output channels, followed\nby global layer normalization (gLN). This step projects each\ntime–frequency (T–F) unit into a D-dimensional latent embedding, resulting in a tensor of shape D × T × F . The decoder\nmirrors the encoder by applying a 3 × 3 2D transposed convolution (Deconv2D) with 2C output channels, representing the predicted real and imaginary components for all C target sources.\n2.3. The TF-MossFormer Separator\n\n2.1. Overview of TF-MossFormer Architecture\nFig. 2 illustrates our TF-MossFormer architecture. The\ninput mixture waveform x is first transformed into the\ntime–frequency domain using STFT, producing real and imaginary components XReal ∈ RT ×F and XImag. ∈ RT ×F , where\nT and F are the number of frames and frequency bins. The\nreal and imaginary parts are concatenated as X ∈ R2×T ×F\nand passed through a 2D convolutional (Conv2D) encoder followed by global Layer Normalization (gLN) to project the features into a feature representative space. The core separator\nconsists of B stacked TF-MossFormer blocks, each comprising two sub-modules: the frequency module and the temporal\nmodule. Both modules share the same architecture but perform on alternative sequence dimensions. The frequency module models spectral dependencies across frequency bins along\nthe frequency path, while the temporal module models temporal dependencies across time frames along the time path. By\nalternately modeling frequency and time dependencies, the network progressively refines the representation while efficiently\ncovering the entire time–frequency context. The decoder uses a\ntransposed convolution (Deconv2D) layer to reconstruct the estimated real and imaginary spectra, which are then transformed\nback to the time domain using the inverse STFT (iSTFT) to obtain the separated waveform signals.\n\nThe encoded representation is passed to the TF-MossFormer\nseparator, which consists of B stacked TF-MossFormer blocks.\nWithin each block, the spectro-temporal modeling is performed\nto progressively refine the local–global dependencies for the\nlatent TF embeddings. As depicted in Fig. 2(a), each TFMossFormer block contains two sequential modeling modules:\na frequency modeling module and a temporal modeling module, both sharing an identical architecture. The module architecture is shown in Fig. 1(b), where the input tensor is first\npermuted to align the modeling dimension (frequency or time)\nwith the sequence axis. The permuted input is passed through a\nconvolutional SwiGLU feed-forward network (Conv-SwiGLU)\n[14], followed by a residual connection to preserve the original representation. Next, Root Mean Square Group Normalization (RMSGroupNorm) [14] is applied to stabilize training and\nimprove convergence. The normalized features are then processed by the core Local & Global Multi-Head Self-Attention\n(MHSA) module, which integrates content-aware local attention (via sliding windows) and global attention to jointly model\nfine-grained dependencies and long-range context. The output\nis again passed through a Conv-SwiGLU module and added\nback via residual connection before being permuted back to its\noriginal shape. This design ensures balanced local and global\nrepresentation learning while maintaining efficiency through\n\n\fTable 1: Hyperparameter notations and model configurations\nfor TF-MambaFormer (S), (M), and (L).\n\nLinear\nConcat\n\nSymbol Description\nh\n\nScaled Dot-Product Attention\n\nLinear\n\nLinear\n\nLinear\n\nFig. 3: An overview of the local attention module, which performs multi-head self-attention using sliding windows. Each\nattention head operates on a fixed-size window of the input sequence.\nresidual pathways and normalization.\n2.3.1. Convolution Gated Local and Global Attention\nWe apply both local and global attention with convolution gating in the TF-MossFormer separator to capture complementary\nshort- and long-range dependencies in speech spectrograms.\nOur global attention is a standard Multi-Head Self-Attention\n(MHSA) mechanism [19], every frame in a sequence attends\nto every other frame as depicted in Fig. 1(a). For the temporal\nsequence X ∈ RT ×D T, the query (Qi ), key (Ki ), and value\n(Vi ) matrices are the i-th head projections of size T ×dh , where\ndh = D/h is the hidden dimension of each head. Our global\nMHSA computes the attention of each head as:\n\u0012\n\u0013\nQi K ⊤\nheadglobal,i = softmax √ i\nVi .\n(1)\ndh\nAll heads are concatenated to form the full attention matrix:\n\u0001\nMHSAglobal (X) = Concat headglobal,1 , . . . , headglobal,h WO ,\n(2)\nwhere WO is the output projection matrix. This operation has\ncomplexity O(T 2 D) due to the dense QK ⊤ computation.\nComplementing the global attention, we present local attention to focus on short-range time–frequency patterns to preserve fine-grained continuity. As depicted in Fig. 1(b), it captures context at varying distances from each frame. Our local attention adopts the sliding-window multi-head attention as\ndepicted in Fig. 3. The local attention restricts each frame\nt to attend only to frames within a local window N (t) =\n{t − w−1\n, . . . , t, . . . , t + w−1\n}, where w is the window size.\n2\n2\nThe attention for head i becomes:\n\u0012\n\u0013\nQi (t)Ki (N (t))⊤\n√\nheadlocal,i (t) = softmax\nVi (N (t)),\ndh\n(3)\nwhere Qi (t) ∈ R1×dh is the query for frame t, Ki (N (t)) ∈\nRw×dh are the keys within the window, and Vi (N (t)) are the\ncorresponding values. This reduces complexity to O(T wD),\nwhich scales linearly with T for a fixed w.\nWe further augment local and global attention with convolutional gates as shown in Fig. 2(c). The gate consists of a\nConv1D layer followed by Swish activation. Since attention ordering affects performance, we implemented three block variants (V1-V3) and ran an ablation study to identify the most effective arrangement for our model.\n\nS\n\nM\n\nL\n\nD\nB\nH\nO\nK\nS\nh\nwF\nwT\n\nEmbedding dimension of each TF bin\n96 128 128\nNumber of TF-MossFormer blocks\n4 6\n9\nHidden dimension in Conv-SwiGLU\n256 384 384\nOutput dimension in Conv-Gate\n96 128 128\nKernel size in Conv1D and Deconv1D\n4 4\n4\nStride in Conv1D and Deconv1D\n1 1\n1\nNumber of heads in self-attention\n4 4 4\nSliding-window length for frequency path 7 7 7\nSliding-window length for temporal path 31 31 31\n\n−\n\nNumber of parameters [M]\n\n6.0 16.9 25.4\n\n2.3.2. The Convolution Modules\nLocal attention captures nearby context but needs many layers\nfor broader integration. To improve global feature mixing efficiently, we add Conv-SwiGLU blocks (Fig. 2(b)), combining attention’s adaptive weighting with convolutional feature\nextraction. Each block applies RMSGroupNorm, two parallel\n1D convolutions, a Swish-gated element-wise modulation, and\na final 1D deconvolution to restore embedding size. Following [14], we place Conv-SwiGLU before and after the local and\nglobal attention layers.\n\n3. Experiments\n3.1. Dataset & Experimental Setup\nWe validated our proposed TF-MossFormer on the widely-used\nWSJ0-2mix dataset, which benchmarks monaural speech separation. The dataset is comprised of three distinct sets: a training\nset of 20,000 ( 30 hours), a validation set of 5,000 ( 10 hours),\nand a test set of 3,000 ( 5 hours) two-speaker mixtures. The\nclean utterances are sourced from the WSJ0 corpus. In each\nmixture, the two utterances are randomly selected from WSJ0\nand fully overlapped, with their relative energy levels randomly\nchosen from the signal-to-noise ratios (SNR) between -5 dB and\n5 dB. The test set is generated in the same way. Notably, speakers in the test set are distinct from those in the training and validation sets, ensuring a non-blind evaluation. All audio clips are\nsampled at 8 kHz.\nAll experiments were conducted using the ESPnet pipeline\nwith SI-SDR loss [20]. Table 1 summarizes the key hyperparameters and default configurations for our three model sizes.\nFor data preparation, we used a 16 ms STFT window with an\n8 ms hop size and segmented all input audio into 4 s clips. Each\nmixture was normalized by its standard deviation, and the batch\nsize was set to 4. For optimization, we employed the AdamW\noptimizer [21] with a weight decay of 1 × 10−2 . The learning\nrate was linearly warmed up to 1 × 10−3 during the first 4,000\nsteps, followed by a scheduler that halved the learning rate if the\nvalidation loss failed to improve for three consecutive epochs.\nTraining was conducted for up to 150 epochs, with early stopping applied after 10 stagnant epochs. To ensure stability, the\nL2 norm of the gradient was clipped to 5.\n3.2. Ablation Study\nAs shown in Table 2, we evaluated several sliding-window configurations for TF-MossFormer (S) on WSJ0-2Mix, keeping the\nwindow length identical across all attention heads for ease of\ntuning. The setting of wT = 31 and wF = 7 achieves the best\n\n\fTable 2: Ablation study of TF-MossFormer performance with\ndifferent sliding-window lengths.\nModel (S)\n\nTable 4: Performance comparison of TF-MossFormer (S) with\nstate-of-the-art models of similar scale on the WSJ0-2Mix\ndataset.\n\nSliding-Window(wT , wF ) SI-SDRi SDRi MACS [G/s]\n\nTF-MossFormer\nTF-MossFormer\nTF-MossFormer\nTF-MossFormer\nTF-MossFormer\nTF-MossFormer\n\n(31, 7)\n(15, 7)\n(65, 7)\n(31, 3)\n(31, 15)\nFull Length\n\n22.61\n22.51\n22.56\n22.53\n22.47\n22.38\n\n22.77\n22.68\n22.73\n22.69\n22.66\n22.58\n\n99.5\n99.4\n99.7\n99.5\n99.5\n100.3\n\nTable 3: Ablation study of TF-MossFormer performance with\ndifferent configurations of local-global attention.\nModel (S)\nTF-MossFormer(V1)\nTF-MossFormer(V2)\nTF-MossFormer(V3)\nTF-MossFormer(V4)\n\nSliding-Window(T-F) SI-SDRi SDRi MACS [G/s]\n(31, 7)\n(31, 7)\n(31, 7)\n(31, 7)\n\n22.61\n22.45\n22.49\n22.51\n\n22.77\n22.60\n22.63\n22.62\n\n99.5\n99.5\n99.5\n99.3\n\nresult, with 22.61 dB SI-SDRi (22.77 dB SDRi) while maintaining manageable computation at 99.5 G MACS/s, slightly\noutperforming both the narrower 15-frame and the wider 65frame time windows. A frequency span of 7 bands is also\npreferable to smaller (3 bands) or larger (15 bands) choices. Using full-length windows yields the weakest performance (22.38\ndB). These results indicate that TF-MossFormer favors moderate time–frequency window sizes that balance local detail and\nefficiency. Table 3 evaluates the local–global attention layouts and convolution gating for TF-MossFormer (S) on WSJ02Mix. All models used the (31,7) sliding window. The cascade ordering—local attention followed by global attention\n(V1)—achieves the best results (22.61 dB SI-SDRi, 22.77 dB\nSDRi). Reversing the order (V2) reduces SI-SDRi to 22.45 dB,\nwhile the parallel local–global design (V3) performs slightly\nbetter than V2 (22.49 dB). Removing convolutional gating from\nV1 (V4) also degrades performance to 22.51 dB. These findings\nsuggest that applying local attention before global aggregation\nhelps preserve fine-grained spectral continuity, and that convolutional gating yields measurable gains in feature selection.\n3.3. Experimental Results\nOur experimental results on WSJ0-2Mix, presented in Tables\n4 and 5, comprehensively evaluate TF-MossFormer (configuration V1) across three model scales. The small-scale variant TFMossFormer(S), with just 6.0M parameters and 99.5 G MACS/s\ncomputational cost, achieves 22.61 dB SI-SDRi (22.77 dB\nSDRi), demonstrating superior separation quality compared to\nother compact models. It notably outperforms both the standard\nTF-Locoformer(S) and our reproduced TF-Locoformer(S*)\nwith increased dimensionality (D =112), which achieves 22.2\ndB SI-SDRi at higher computational cost. The comparison with\nSPMamba is particularly revealing - TF-MossFormer(S) delivers better performance (by 0.1 dB SI-SDRi) while requiring\nless than half the computations, highlighting our architecture’s\nefficiency advantages. At medium scale, TF-MossFormer(M)\n(16.9M parameters, 283.4 G MACS/s) reaches 24.0 dB SI-SDRi\n(24.20 dB SDRi), significantly surpassing both TF-GridNet and\nTF-Locoformer(M) in performance while maintaining substantially lower computational requirements than TF-GridNet. This\ndemonstrates excellent scaling properties of our architecture.\nThe large-scale TF-MossFormer(L) (25.4M parameters, 425.0\nG MACS/s) establishes new state-of-the-art results with 24.4 dB\n\nModel (S)\n\nParam.[M] SI-SDRi SDRi MACS [G/s]\n\nConv-TasNet [5]\n\n5.6\n\n15.3\n\n15.6\n\n10.23\n\nA-FRCNN [22]\nDualPathRNN [6]\nVSUNOS [23]\nDPTNet [4]\nS4M [24]\nSepMamba+DM [25]\nDPMamba [26]\nTF-Locoformer(S) [14]\nTF-Locoformer(S*) [14]\nSPMamba [13]\n\n6.1\n2.6\n7.5\n2.6\n3.6\n7.2\n8.1\n5.0\n6.0\n6.1\n\n18.3\n18.8\n20.1\n20.2\n20.5\n21.2\n21.4\n22.0\n22.2\n22.5\n\n18.6\n19.0\n20.4\n20.6\n20.7\n21.4\n21.6\n22.1\n22.3\n22.7\n\n125.3\n85.3\n102.5\n38.7\n85.9\n100.3\n238.6\n\nTF-MossFormer(S)\n\n6.0\n\n22.6\n\n22.8\n\n99.5\n\nTable 5: Performance comparison of TF-MossFormer (M) and\n(L) with state-of-the-art models of similar scale on the WSJ02Mix dataset.\nModel (M&L)\n\nParam.[M] SI-SDRi SDRi MACS [G/s]\n\nTF-GridNet [12]\nTF-Locoformer (M) [14]\nTF-MossFormer(M)\n\n14.4\n15.0\n16.9\n\n23.5\n23.6\n24.0\n\n23.6\n23.8\n24.2\n\n445.5\n251.1\n283.4\n\nWavesplit [27]\nSepFormer+DM [7]\nSepMamba+DM [25]\nMossFormer(L)+DM [8]\nDPMamba [26]\nQPDN [28]\nSepTDA2 [29]\nMossFormer2(L)+DM [9]\nTF-Locoformer(L) [14]\n\n29.0\n25.7\n22.0\n42.1\n59.8\n200\n21.2\n55.7\n22.6\n\n22.2\n22.3\n22.7\n22.8\n23.4\n23.6\n24.0\n24.1\n24.2\n\n22.3\n22.4\n22.9\n23.6\n23.9\n24.3\n\n257.9\n256.7\n336.9\n377.1\n\nTF-MossFormer(L)\n\n25.4\n\n24.4\n\n24.5\n\n425.0\n\nSI-SDRi (24.5 dB SDRi), outperforming all frequency-domain\ncompetitors including TF-Locoformer(L) and SepTDA2 , as\nwell as challenging time-domain baselines like MossFormer\nand MossFormer2 with dynamic mixing. These consistent gains\nacross all model sizes, from compact to large configurations, robustly validate the effectiveness of our local-global attention design in achieving superior separation quality while maintaining\ncomputational efficiency. The results particularly highlight our\narchitecture’s advantage in modeling both fine-grained spectrotemporal details and long-range dependencies simultaneously.\n\n4. Conclusion\nWe presented TF-MossFormer, a hybrid time–frequency transformer that combines adaptive local attention with global attention for monaural speech separation. Our main contributions are: (1) content-aware sliding-window attention for\nadaptive spectro-temporal modeling; (2) an optimized local–global attention configuration; and (3) convolutional gating to improve feature selection and information flow. Extensive experiments on WSJ0-2Mix show that TF-MossFormer\ndelivers state-of-the-art separation performance across multiple model scales while maintaining favorable parameter and\ncomputation efficiency compared to existing time-domain and\nfrequency-domain baselines.\n\n\f5. References\n[1] H. Erdogan, J. R. Hershey, S. Watanabe, and J. L. Roux, “Phase\nsensitive and recognition-boosted speech separation using deep\nrecurrent neural networks,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2015, p. 708–712.\n[2] Y. Luo and N. Mesgarani, “TasNet: time-domain audio separation\nnetwork for real-time, single-channel speech separation,” in Proc.\nof ICASSP, 2018.\n\n[21] I. Loshchilov and F. Hutter, “Decoupled weight decay regularization,” in Proc. ICLR, 2018.\n[22] X. Hu, K. Li, W. Zhang, Y. Luo, J.-M. Lemercier, and T. Gerkmann, “Speech separation using an asynchronous fully recurrent\nconvolutional neural network,” in Proc. of NeurIPS, 2021.\n[23] E. Nachmani, Y. Adi, and L. Wolf, “Voice separation with an unknown number of multiple speakers,” in Proc. of ICML, 2020.\n\n[3] ——, “Real-time single-channel dereverberation and separation\nwith time-domain audio separation network,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2018.\n\n[24] C. Chen, C.-H. H. Yang, K. Li, Y. Hu, P.-J. Ku, and E. S. Chng, “A\nneural state-space model approach to efficient speech separation,”\nin Proc. of Interspeech, 2023.\n\n[4] J. Chen, Q. Mao, and D. Liu, “Dual-Path Transformer Network:\nDirect context-aware modeling for end-to-end monaural speech\nseparation,” in Proc. of Interspeech, 2020.\n\n[25] T. H. Avenstrup, B. Elek, I. L. Mádi, A. B. Schin, M. Mørup,\nB. S. Jensen, and K. F. Olsen, “SepMamba: State-space models\nfor speaker separation using mamba,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2024.\n\n[5] Y. Luo and N. Mesgarani, “Conv-TasNet: Surpassing ideal\ntime–frequency magnitude masking for speech separation,”\nIEEE/ACM transactions on audio, speech, and language processing, vol. 27, no. 8, p. 1256–1266, 2019.\n\n[26] X. Jiang, C. Han, and N. Mesgarani, “Dual-path Mamba: Short\nand long-term bidirectional selective structured state space models for speech separation,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2025.\n\n[6] Y. Luo, Z. Chen, and T. Yoshioka, “Dual-Path RNN: Efficient long\nsequence modeling for time-domain single-channel speech separation,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2020.\n[7] C. Subakan, M. Ravanelli, S. Cornell, M. Bronzi, and J. Zhong,\n“Attention is all you need in speech separation,” in Proc. of\nICASSP, 2021.\n[8] S. Zhao and B. Ma, “MossFormer: Pushing the performance\nlimit of monaural speech separation using gated single-head transformer with convolution-augmented joint self-attentions,” in Proc.\nof ICASSP, 2023.\n[9] S. Zhao, Y. Ma, C. Ni, C. Zhang, H. Wang, T. H. Nguyen,\nK. Zhou, J. Yip, D. Ng, and B. Ma, “MossFormer2: Combining transformer and rnn-free recurrent network for enhanced timedomain monaural speech separation,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2024.\n[10] S. Chen, Y. Wu, Z. Chen, J. Wu, J. Li, T. Yoshioka, C. Wang,\nS. Liu, and M. Zhou, “Continuous speech separation with conformer,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2021, pp. 5749–5753.\n[11] L. Yang, W. Liu, and W. Wang, “TFPSNet: Time-frequency domain path scanning network for speech separation,” in Proc. of\nICASSP, 2022.\n[12] Z.-Q. Wang, S. Cornell, S. Choi, Y. Lee, B.-Y. Kim, and S. Watanabe, “TF-GridNet: Making time-frequency domain models great\nagain for monaural speaker separation,” arXiv:2209.03952, 2023.\n[13] K. Li, G. Chen, R. Yang, and X. Hu, “SPMamba: State-space\nmodel is all you need in speech separation,” arXiv:2404.02063,\n2024.\n[14] K. Saijo, G. Wichern, F. G. Germain, Z. Pan, and J. L. Roux, “TFLocoformer: Transformer with local modeling by convolution for\nspeech separation and enhancement,” in 2024 18th International\nWorkshop on Acoustic Signal Enhancement (IWAENC), 2024.\n[15] I. Beltagy, M. E. Peters, and A. Cohan, “Longformer: The longdocument transformer,” arXiv:2004.05150, 2020.\n[16] M. Zaheer, G. Guruganesh, K. A. Dubey, J. Ainslie, C. Alberti,\nS. Ontanon, P. Pham, A. Ravula, Q. Wang, L. Yang et al., “Big\nbird: Transformers for longer sequences,” Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, vol. 33, 2020.\n[17] N. Ebert, L. Reichardt, D. Stricker, and O. Wasenmüller, “Lightweight vision transformer with parallel local and global selfattention,” arXiv:2307.09120, 2023.\n[18] L. Zhu, X. Wang, Z. Ke, W. Zhang, and R. Lau, “Biformer: Vision\ntransformer with bi-level routing attention,” Proceedings of the\nIEEE/CVF Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR), 2023.\n[19] A. Vaswani, N. Shazeer, N. Parmar, J. Uszkoreit, L. Jones, A. N.\nGomez, L. Kaiser, and I. Polosukhin, “Attention is all you need,”\nin Proc. NIPS, 2017.\n[20] C. Li, J. Shi, W. Zhang, A. S. Subramanian, X. Chang et al.,\n“ESPnet-SE: End-to-end speech enhancement and separation\ntoolkit designed for asr integration,” in Proc. SLT, 2021.\n\n[27] N. Zeghidour and D. Grangier, “Wavesplit: End-to-end speech\nseparation by speaker clustering,” IEEE/ACM Trans. Audio.\nSpeech, Lang. Process., vol. 29, 2021.\n[28] J. Rixen and M. Renz, “QDPN - Quasi-dual-path Network for\nsingle-channel Speech Separation,” in Proc. Interspeech 2022,\n2022, pp. 5353–5357.\n[29] Y. Lee, S. Choi, B.-Y. Kim, Z.-Q. Wang, and S. Watanabe,\n“Boosting unknown-number speaker separation with transformer\ndecoder-based attractor,” in Proc. of ICASSP, 2024.\n\n\f", "numLines": 713, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 713}}}
